<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Slurm:  I can't really agree with you there.  I don't have experince with high-level play in EQ, so I can't speak from experience, but I *do* have a lot of experience working on games for play-balance.   I playtest board and card games as a hobby and work with several companies (Including WotC - Wizards of the Coast).<P>There are times where you want something because it's "class defining" and I appreciate that fact.  That's why I left AC to play EQ because high level play in AC everyone has the same abilities, people who started out as a mage has a slightly better ability to cast spells than someone who started out as a fighter, but the fighter can cast non-offensive spells as good as any mage at high levels.   That was what forced me to leave the game.<P>Based on reading message boards and hearing from friends who have played at high levels, I would agree with you *if* there wasn't a pathing problem with pets.  If they would follow you around, not get lost, not train the whole zone on you, etc, I would strongly agree that it should be one class only.  <P>Assuming it's as bad as everyone says it can be (and I've seen examples of bad pathing with mobs, so I can imagine how bad pets can be at some places) I would have to say it's a good move to give all the pet classes that ability.<P>In EQ2 or any other future games (or even base EQ if they ever fix pathing problems, I doubt they could, too much work) it shouldn't be given to everyone.<P>Taladaen - 36th level Shaman<BR>Playtester for far too many pen&paper RPGs, computer RPGs, CCG/TCGs, board games, etc.
</FONT>
